80. The language of Terence differs far less from that of classical times than does that of Plautus. The latter writer was not only earlier than Terence, but, as we have seen, moved in a different circle of society. He therefore gives us a much larger proportion of purely popular speech, while Terence represents the everyday speech of cultivated Romans.

There are, however, certain archaic features iu the lau· guage of Terence which it will bc worth while to note.
